The proportion of variation explained by each of the principalcomponents are shown in the table below. In terms of GDP, we can see that the contribution of principal component 1 is 94.04% and the contribution of principal component 2 is 4.45%, and the first eigen value is 11.28, the second one is 0.53.In terms of life expectancy, we can see that the contribution of principal component 1 is 92.32% and the contribution of principal component 2 is 5.63%, and the first eigen value is 11.08,the second one is 0.68. There is no certain rule for the number of principal components to be selected, and the analysis should be specific to the actual situation, generally requiring a cumulative contribution rate greater than 85% or an eigenvalue greater than 1,because the higher the variance, the more information.So for both GDP and life expectancy, I would choose two principal components.

Hypothesis test

I will use Hotelling’s T2 one sample test to test whether there was a statistically significant difference between the normalized mean log(GDP) and life expectancy of Asian and European countries in the year 2007. The alternative hypothesis H0: there is no difference between GDP and life expectancy in 2007. We can see that the test value p-value is 0.8182, much bigger than the test value 0.05, so the alternative hypothesis is accepted, that means there was a statistically significant difference between the mean log(GDP) and life expectancy of Asian and European countries in the year 2007.

gdp_asiameans_2007 <- colMeans(gdp_asia_life_2007)
gdp_eur_life_2007 <- gap %>% dplyr::filter(continent=='Europe') %>% dplyr::select(gdpPercap_2007,lifeExp_2007)
gdp_eurmeans_2007 <- colMeans(gdp_eur_life_2007)

HotellingsT2(gdp_asia_life_2007-gdp_asiameans_2007, gdp_eur_life_2007-gdp_eurmeans_2007)
## 
##  Hotelling's two sample T2-test
## 
## data:  gdp_asia_life_2007 - gdp_asiameans_2007 and gdp_eur_life_2007 - gdp_eurmeans_2007
## T.2 = 0.20132, df1 = 2, df2 = 60, p-value = 0.8182
## alternative hypothesis: true location difference is not equal to c(0,0)

I will also use Hotelling’s T2 one sample test to test whether there was a statistically significant difference between the normalized mean log(GDP) and life expectancy of Asian and European countries in the year 1957. The alternative hypothesis H0: v. We can see that the test value p-value is 0.07629, bigger than the test value 0.05, so the alternative hypothesis is accepted, that means there had difference between the mean log(GDP) and life expectancy of Asian and European countries in the year 1957.

set.seed(450) 
test_d.index <- sample(1:142, size=12)
model.test <- gap[test_d.index,]
model.train <- gap[-test_d.index,]

gdp_.lda<-lda(continent ~ gdpPercap_1952+gdpPercap_1957+gdpPercap_1962+gdpPercap_1967+gdpPercap_1972+gdpPercap_1977+gdpPercap_1982+gdpPercap_1987+gdpPercap_1992+gdpPercap_1997+gdpPercap_2002+gdpPercap_2007, model.train)
gdp.pred <- predict(gdp_.lda, model.test)
print(paste("The predictive accuracy is ", 
sum(gdp.pred$class== model.test$continent)/dim(model.test)[1]*100, "%"))
## [1] "The predictive accuracy is  75 %"
lif_.lda<-lda(continent~ lifeExp_1952+lifeExp_1957+lifeExp_1962+lifeExp_1967+lifeExp_1972+lifeExp_1977+lifeExp_1982+lifeExp_1987+lifeExp_1992+lifeExp_1997+lifeExp_2002+lifeExp_2007, model.train)
lif.pred <- predict(lif_.lda, model.test)
print(paste("The predictive accuracy is ", 
sum(lif.pred$class== model.test$continent)/dim(model.test)[1]*100, "%"))

The table shows that some continents has been misclassified as other continents by the classifier in terms of GDP and life expectancy, which is one of the factors affecting the predictive accuracy.

The dendrograms show that Ward’s method most clearly finds four distinct clusters.

gap.scaled <- gap
gap.scaled[,3:26] <- scale(gap[,3:26])
#single method
gap.scaled_single <- hclust(dist(gap.scaled[,3:26],method="euclidean"),method="single")
plot(gap.scaled_single, labels=gap$continent ,cex=0.7)

#complete method
gap.scaled_complete <- hclust(dist(gap.scaled[,3:26],method="euclidean"),method="complete")
plot(gap.scaled_complete, labels=gap$continent,cex=0.7)

#ward method
gap.scaled_ward <- hclust(dist(gap.scaled[,3:26],method="euclidean"),method="ward.D2")
plot(gap.scaled_ward, labels=gap$continent,cex=0.7)

#average method
gap.scaled_average <- hclust(dist(gap.scaled[,3:26],method="euclidean"),method="average")
plot(gap.scaled_average, labels=gap$continent,cex=0.7)

Since Ward’s method divides the data into 4 categories, so k=4. The confusion matrices show again that when cut into four clusters, Single’s method do a good job of finding the four groups of continents.

Comparing the k-means clustering and the hierarchical clustering using the Ward’s method, it is found that Oceania is clustered in the last category in both methods, and Asia appears in each category. In addition, I don’t think they has cluster countries naturally by continent. Single’s method should be the way to cluster countries naturally by continent.
